text: hi everyone karthini tuntano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new mitsky
album laurel hell back with her sixth
full-length lp following up her ever so
popular be the cowboy in 2018 which
instantly made her one of the most
popular singers and songwriters on the
indie circuit there were spots of this
record i thought were spectacular but
love for the entire thing sort of eluded
me sure it was more high production than
her earlier releases but many of the
songs lacked development and
instrumentally there wasn't really a
strong sense of direction going anywhere
as the tracklist brought this under
season buffet of art pop dream pop and
new wave but mitsky's previous projects
were much rarer by comparison maybe it
was a an instance of an awkward
transition into something bigger so i
went into laurel hell hoping to hear a
stronger sense of self though the
teasers had me skeptical the first of
which was working for the knife which
currently stands as one of my least
favorite mitsky tracks ever the
instrumental on this one is just so
messy and unflattering first off is the
intro supposed to sound like a bad
impression of the knife then suddenly
completely fades away from that into
this slow tedious clanging banging
instrumental of dream industrial indie
rock every sound it casually throws into
the mix to build it up only makes it
sound more obnoxious and sloppy yeah i
just wasn't impressed with this song on
first listen as i have revisited it for
this review it has not grown on me at
all further singles love me more heat
lightning and the only heartbreaker
we're leagues better in terms of song
structure and instrumentation but we're
all still more or less nostalgic
synth-pop throwbacks something i'd say
there's no shortage of these days and
unfortunately i failed to see what
mitski brings to this particular sound
on this record especially with how
derivatives some of these tracks are
running like for as fun and as
exhilarating as the hook on love me more
is there are elements of it that sort of
sound like flash dances maniac the beat
that kicks off the only heartbreaker
sounds like the intro to five or six
different new wave hits the instrumental
is pretty extravagant and blood pumping
yes but i wonder how well a move like
this is going to go over with longtime
mitsky fans because the magic of this
track isn't really in any detailed or
confessional lyricism it's really more
about this sparkling melodramatic chorus
so with the rest of the record i was
more or less hoping for something that
would wow me in the deep cuts but
they more or less ended up being fine
there's the patient dronie intro cut
valentine texas that features some
droney synth chords and sparse beats
kind of sounds like a beach house cut
from the late 2000s love the way the
synthesizers blossom and layer up as the
track progresses mitsky's vocals
somberly guide the listener into the
rest of the album staysoft is a dreamy
disco cut with a bump and groove fun
synth embellishments and rich bright
pianos as well what also stuck out to me
about this track is how well mitsky
strikes this balance between pop appeal
but then also writing a song that's
pretty thoughtful and detailed lyrically
really straddles this border between
being really dark and sexy as well the
song everyone is one of many slow
burners in the track list here and i
also think hits harder as a poem than it
does a piece of music the slow throbbing
beats and mitsky's middling vocals don't
really leave as strong an impression on
me as her comments on the dangers of
youthful naivete i felt mostly the same
way about there's nothing left for you
the bright rush of synths and guitars
and soaring vocals in the second half is
bold and does hit hard i also love the
way it kind of disappears almost as if
it was just a figment of my imagination
but the whole thing works better as a
poetic meditation about being totally
and completely done with someone
emotionally however these feelings don't
seem completely mutual on the following
should have been me where mitsuki
describes her ex as having found someone
who looks just like her now saying must
be lonely loving someone trying to find
their way out of a maze it would kill me
if that was an ex's assessment of me
maybe it is
yeah
the final moments of this lp i'm a
little mixed on because the progression
of this narrative is a bit jumpy we
switch from kind of bitterly judging the
other person who's also just trying to
move on with their life and maybe yeah
they haven't got everything quite
figured out yet two then disconnecting
from that and any larger narrative
completely on the song i guess which is
really another internal monologue being
presented as this dreamy ethereal
musical meditation which once more hits
bland is utterly unmemorable musically
but mitzki's words about wanting to hold
on to the calm after the storm of a
rocky relationship those hit hard those
words resonate with me uh pretty hard
personally she even leaves the song
saying thank you before it just
completely disappears into the ether the
track ends up being sort of a final but
fleeting thought before we transition
into that's our lamp which is uh turning
up the heat with a louder more rocking
instrumental it ends up being sort of a
credits roll moment for the lp with
mitsky reflecting back on this really
chaotic moment where she is running out
of the apartment after a fight but
there's something kind of lacking about
the track as an overall song and a final
moment for the lp because there's a
severe lack of detail in the progression
of this fight the whole scenario overall
the faint disco grooves on the track are
kind of overpowered by mitski's vocals
which
aren't the best performance on the
entire lp there's something about the
song that feels almost like karaoke i
just think it's really awkward and
somewhat inconclusive note to finish
things on even if it is just an
afterthought or a quick
snapshot of a moment at an earlier time
so final thoughts on laurel hell are
tough to sum up honestly there are
aspects of it that i prefer over be the
cowboy uh be it the
instrumental consistency or the breakup
theme but by that same token on the
songwriting front on the instrumental
front there is something severely
missing from a lot of these tracks
that's not to say there are highlights
that there aren't good parts of course
but laurel hell overall is just not an
lp that i see myself either uh in whole
or in pieces coming back to anytime soon
